The implementations are different.

Source project: When using a Map to create the JSONObject, the field of this object creates a reference to the map. 
So when map changes, the JSONObject's map filed also changes.


Target project: When using a Map to create the JSONObject, the field of this object create a new empty map and copy all key-value pairs into the new map.

There are 10 out of 29 test methods failed after the migration. (10 fail 19 pass)

The reasons are different case by case, but all of them are not related to the target method endArray.

Failure reasons:
1. The source project can handle the special double values such as NaN, -Infinity and Infinity, while the target JSONReader and readObject cannot read them as double.
2. When accepting the some values such as "[truey]" into JSONReader and read the start array symbol([), target will throw error while source project can at least read [ at first.
3. The target project cannot parse mixed case literals to boolean. When accepting "[True,TruE,False,FALSE,NULL,nulL]" and start reading the first object, it will throw an exception. The source project can handle it.
4. Target project cannot handle the array such as "[true,,true]", it will throw a syntax error.
5. Target project allows multiple top level values such as "[] []", while a test is to test if error is thrown.
6. Source project can skip wrong symbols such ")", but target project will throw an error.
7. When calling readString, target project can not accept the input such as "[b, c, d]", it must be "[\"b\",\"c\",\"d\"]".

So overall, the failures and errors are all caused by the different implementation of source target classes and the methods inside, such as readObject, readString and nextString, nextDouble and it's not related to endArray.
